Virtual Field Campaigns in Model Datasets

¶

Suvarchal K. Cheedela
Nikolay Koldunov, Rajka Juhrbandt, Thomas Jung
Willi Rath, Benoit Bovy

Hello Everyone, Today I am going to talk about our project virtual field campaigns, The reason I wanted to give the talk is 1. its been almost 7 months I have started and I wanted to give a status update. 2. a teaser of what is coming 3. entrain any related use cases, data you might have for mutual benefit 4. upcoming plans. it will be abit technical, but i hope you can relate to aspects of it. I work closely with our loved Nikolay, Rajka - a bright intern, who will continue at AWI for her master's thesis. We also have other collaborators from Kiel who are working on other aspects of the work.

What is it about?

¶

We have data from various expeditions, we want to know what happens in our models along these transects and conduct new virtual expeditions.¶

Why?

  • Bring models and observations closer. e.g., supplement expeditions with model data.
  • Evaluate and improve models.
  • May guide future expeditions (using our H.R simulations).

Target Expeditions: MOSAiC, other expeditions from pangaea repository and some standard transects.
Target models: FESOM2, NEMO, and CMIP6

There is vast collection of data from expeditions, for instance pangaea contains datasets from various expeditions. Idea is can we see what happens in model datasets along these paths of these expeditions. You can think of it like a satellite simulatior for field campaings. Why would we want to do that

  1. to bring models and observations closer in this context. e.g, then we can supplement obs with some data from models.
  2. we can use the data from expeditions to evaluate models and improve
  3. ability to do expeditions in models may act as guidance for future obs campaigns.

Model datasets we initially targeted are FESOM, NEMO but then soon realized with the machinery we plan would be more useful to a broader community if we target CMIP6 models.

Approach ¶

Because picking a path from pangaea and selecting data from models is a repetative process, we want to build a app or dashboard usuable by broad level of users.¶

Not just have a sleek app with limited purpose but build reusable (Python) components that can be used in other contexts.

Components:¶

  • Exploring expeditions: make access to pangaea datasets and standard paths
  • CMIP6 accessor: simplify cmip6 dataprocessing (and possibly access)
  • FESOM: contribute to pyfesom2 development ( and increase update of FESOM simulations)
  • NEMO: not going to talk about it.
  • Extensible app: app that is entensible uses above components.

...and inevitably we need to address data access/distribution.

Component: Exploring expeditions ¶

pangaeapy is a python library that loads pangaea datasets into python as tables. Our thin wrapper around it standadizes and builds metadata-aware datasets in xarray, makes certain operations easier (e.g., plotting) and also hosts a collection of standard paths.

Component: CMIP6 data accessor¶

CMIP6 data comes in different "shapes, sizes and colors"

Raw seaice concentration data examples: 

MRI-ESM2-0: siconc [time, y, x] 
CESM2: siconc [time, nj, ni] 
BCC-ESM1: siconc [time, lat, lon] 
AWI-ESM-1-1-LR: siconc [time, ncells]

ESMValTools processed thetao monthly climatology examples: 

NorESM2-MM: thetao [month_number, rho, j, i] 
CESM2: thetao [month_number, lev, nlat, nlon] 
MRI-ESM2-0: thetao [month_number, lev, dim2, dim3] 
IPSL-CM6A-LR: thetao [month_number, olevel, dim2, dim3]

Example: say to plot crossection along a longitude

model1: plot(x='lon', y='lev')  
model2: plot(x='longitude', y='depth') ... and so on

Component: CMIP6 data accessor¶

CMIP6 data comes in different "shapes, sizes and colors"

We want to address these aspects in our library component, model_data, to make dealing with these datasets easier.

Aspects:¶

  • Homoginize data: rename, reorganize data so that all datasets can be addressed in a similar way.
  • Selection: select data along paths, and regions.
  • Interpolation (regridding): interpolate data to a target grid so that we can compute sums and differences.
  • Address data as collections: group data into collections and simplify processing further.

CMIP6 Accessor: Homoginizing datasets ¶

We want to homoginize data (rename, restructure) on the fly so that we can operate on them similarly.

CMIP6 Accessor: Selection ¶

We want to select points in model representative of path along expedition. For demonstration a point (lon, lat) in path.

  • For rectilinear grids, nearest neighbor selection is closest lat, then lon or vice versa.
  • For Curvilinear or unstructured grids, each dimention is function of lat,lon. Distance to grids points can be the metric.
    • project, build tree, query tree

CMIP6 Accessor: Interpolation ¶

Selection on nearest neighbor might not be best representative (e.g., close to land)

In [16]:
sample_dataset = xr.open_dataset('/home/suvarchal/AWI/AO_apps/data_ori/thetao_Omon_IPSL-CM6A-LR_historical_gn_mean_1979_2005.nc')
nn_selection = sample_dataset.cmip6.sel(path=mosaic_all_legs)
nn_selection_tol = sample_dataset.cmip6.sel(path=mosaic_all_legs, tolerance=100000)
wa_selection_tol = sample_dataset.cmip6.sel(path=mosaic_all_legs, tolerance=100000, method='inverse_weighted')
In [17]:
fig, axs = plt.subplots(3)
fig.set_size_inches(10,8)
nn_selection.thetao.plot(x='ncells', yincrease=False, levels=np.arange(-2,2,0.2), ax=axs[0])
nn_selection_tol.thetao.plot(x='ncells', yincrease=False, levels=np.arange(-2,2,0.2), ax=axs[1])
wa_selection_tol.thetao.plot(x='ncells', yincrease=False, levels=np.arange(-2,2,0.2), ax=axs[2])
plt.tight_layout()
  • when tolerance is specified, we can also compute stderr, additionally check for significane if needed.
  • regridding of model data to a ref grid (obs). if we want to compute differences.

  • Lack of full support for unstructured grids in standard libraries means we have to provide ways for common operations: pyfesom2.
